:20). Living in the 11th century  bc , Samuel was a Hebrew judge and prophet of the greatest historical importance, who established the Hebrew monarchy, anointing as king both Saul and, later, David. In the Authorized Version two books of the Old Testament are named after him, although in Roman Catholic and Orthodox versions of the Bible they are known as the first and second Book of Kings. The story of Samuel being called by God while still a child serving in the house of Eli the priest (1 Samuel 3) is of great vividness and has moved countless generations. In England and America the name was particularly popular among the 16th-century Puritans and among Nonconformists from the 17th to the 19th century. It became fashionable again in the 1990s."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Samuel Oxford was born in 1475, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Bathsheba. He died about 1551, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1475–abt 1551":"1475–umbes 1551","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1500–1518":"1500–1518","1475–1551":"1475–1551","1500":"1500","1475":"1475","after 1518":"pärast 1518","1551":"1551","1518":"1518","1480":"1480","abt 1551":"umbes 1551","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bratton, Wiltshire, England":"Bratton, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bratton, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bratton, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1475–abt 1551":"1475–noin 1551","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","1500–1518":"1500–1518","1475–1551":"1475–1551","1500":"1500","1475":"1475","after 1518":"1518 jälkeen","1551":"1551","1518":"1518","1480":"1480","abt 1551":"noin 1551","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bratton, Wiltshire, England":"Bratton, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bratton, Wiltshire, E